According to BBSI director of research and statistics Dr. Marlene Ho, who along with Associate Marie Harewood conducted the survey, more than four in every five (83 per cent) women who are single parents are either not working, or are solely responsible for caring for their children and managing the house.

That is consistent with the general characteristic of most single parent households in Netem Project 9 – Women and the Labour Force, which showed almost 77 per cent of both single mother and single father families were largely dependent on one individual’s income to cover total expenditures.

The survey looked at the experiences of single, separating, divorced and widowed women, and the work force and felt positive about getting into some form of employment. It also found that close to 70 per cent of the respondents had 11 years or less of education, with 33 per cent having no education, and 36 per cent only having primary school level education.

Among those who did have education or some form of tertiary education, Dr. Ho pointed out that most of them were interested in returning to work or do something to help generate income in their new circumstances.
